  "proof_statements": {
    "T1": "For common state, action and loss spaces, if E1 is an observation-only Markov garbling of E2, every randomized rule under E1 has a composed randomized rule under E2 with identical statewise risk; hence unrestricted Bayes optimal risk under E2 is no larger for every prior.",
    "T2": "The exact finite S1 and repaired S10 objects exhibit a Blackwell-richer experiment whose registered restricted-policy risk is strictly larger than the coarser registered-policy risk while unrestricted risk is nonincreasing.",
    "T3": "If two randomized action kernels are equal P_theta^E-almost surely for every state in the comparison, then their statewise action-loss laws and risks are equal; any prior or registered group aggregation is equal, so incremental fixed-policy risk value is zero.",
    "T4": "Under equal prior on two states, common observation space, disjoint optimal-action sets with an explicit decoder, and regret at least Delta for every nonoptimal action, every randomized decision rule has average regret at least (Delta/2)*(1-TV(P0,P1)).",
    "T5": "For K uniformly distributed states with state-specific optimal actions and wrong-action regret at least Delta, average regret is at least Delta*[1-((1/K)sum_j KL(P_j||P_bar)+log 2)/log K] under the registered finite Fano conditions; the right side may be truncated below at zero.",
    "T6": "For the exact S5 ten-group loss distributions, the policy improves mean loss and nine group losses but worsens worst-group loss; its upper-loss CVaR exceeds the reference exactly on the candidate region alpha in (13/20,1), subject to C85T derivation or invalidation.",
    "T7": "Under E exp(lambda*(xi_i-xi_star)) <= exp(lambda^2*sigma_i^2/2), first-argmax selection satisfies P(selected outside A_epsilon) <= min(1,sum_{i:Delta_i>epsilon} exp[-Delta_i^2/(2*sigma_i^2)]), without an independence assumption."
  },
